    <h2>Silk router</h2>
    <p>Silk router is a routing library that follows very simple concept. If you are familiar with custom events, you should be able to learn <code>silkrouter</code> with ease.</p>
    <p>Let's begin...</p>
    <h3>Installation</h3>
    <p>
        <pre>
            <code>
    npm install --save silkrouter argon-storage</code>
        </pre>
    </p>
    <p>
        <b>Note:</b> Silk router is dependent on <code>argon-storage</code> library for data persistence. This is something you need to install until version 4 comes out. Sorry about that!
    </p>
    <p>
        <pre>
            <code>
    import { router, route, unroute } from 'silkrouter';</code>
        </pre>
    </p>
    <h3>How does it work?</h3>
    <p>Let's compare custom events and silkrouter.</p>
    <p><b>Events:</b></p>
    <pre>
        <code>
    $('selector').on('eventName', handler);</code>
    </pre>
    <p><b>Router:</b></p>
    <pre>
        <code>
    route('/path', handler);</code>
    </pre>
    <p><b>Triggering events:</b></p>
    <pre>
        <code>
    $('selector').trigger('event');</code>
    </pre>
    <p><b>Triggering routes:</b></p>
     <pre>
        <code>
    router.set('/path');</code>
    </pre>
    <p>If you're wondering if there is a live example of silkrouter in action, this project you're viewing is one!</p>
    <p></p>
    <p>SILK router uses history API under the hood.</p>
    <p>SILK router supports following browsers:</p>
    <p><b>IE10+, Edge, Opera, Safari, Chrome, Firefox, Mobile browsers</b></p>
